    think='Now I understand the failures better. Let me look at the screenshots 
and analyze:\n\n1. **open_drawer failed**: The screenshot shows the login page w
ith "欢迎使用 Social World" visible. The DevTools toggle button (`dev_tools_togg
le_button`) IS present in the hierarchy (I can see it in the view_match_list com
mands JSON at bounds [912,1064][1059,1211]). But in `open_drawer`, the app was l
aunched with `clearState: true`, which means it starts fresh at the login page. 
The issue is that `assertVisible: "开发工具"` failed - but looking at the view_m
atch_list hierarchy, the dev_tools button IS there with `accessibilityText: "开
发工具"` and `resource-id: "dev_tools_toggle_button"`. \n\nWait - in the open_dr
awer flow, it does `launchApp: clearState: true` then `assertVisible: "开发工具"
`. The hierarchy from the open_drawer screenshot might not include the dev tools
button. Let me check the screenshot.\n\nActually, looking at the `login` flow wh
ich PASSED - it also uses `clearState: true` and then runs `includes/login-as-te
st-user.yaml`. But `open_drawer` just launches and asserts "开发工具" immediatel
y. The DevTools button might not be visible or the accessibility text might not 
be detected as a text element.\n\nLooking at the code:\n```dart\nSemantics(\n  i
dentifier: \'dev_tools_toggle_button\',\n  label: \'开发工具\',\n  button: true,
\n  container: true,\n```\n\nThe `label` is set to \'开发工具\' but Maestro migh
t not see it as `text` - it sees it as `accessibilityText` or `resource-id`. Let
me check the screenshot for open_drawer.\n\nActually, I should look at the scree
nshots using ReadMediaFile.\n\n2. **swipe_recommendations failed**: "Assertion i
s false: \'欢迎使用 Social World\' is visible" - but this flow uses `login-as-te
st-user.yaml` which asserts this text. Wait, looking at the commands JSON more c
arefully... the login flow PASSED but swipe_recommendations FAILED at the same a
ssertion. The difference might be timing - perhaps when running multiple flows b
ack-to-back, the app state from previous flows affects subsequent ones. Or perha
ps `clearState: true` doesn\'t fully clear the state between flows when run in b
atch mode.\n\nWait - looking at the maestro output:\n- `[Passed] login (18s)` - 
this passed\n- `[Failed] open_drawer (18s)` - this failed at "开发工具" visible\
n- `[Passed] edit_server_url (38s)` - interesting, this passed! But it also uses
`clearState: true` and then taps `dev_tools_toggle_button` by ID, not by text.\n
- `[Failed] swipe_recommendations (18s)` - failed at "欢迎使用 Social World" vis
ible\n- `[Failed] view_match_list (34s)` - failed at `tab_messages` not found\n-
`[Failed] setup (18s)` - failed at "完善资料" visible\n\nThe key insight: `login
` flow passed, but other flows that also use `clearState: true` failed at seeing
the login page. This is because when running multiple flows in a single `maestro
test` command, `clearState: true` only clears app data but if the app is already
running, it might not restart properly or might show a blank screen. Or perhaps 
the flows are run in parallel?\n\nActually, maestro runs flows sequentially in t
he same session. The issue might be that `clearState: true` kills the app and cl
ears data, but when the next flow launches, the app might take time to start. Ho
wever, the error says "Assertion is false: \'欢迎使用 Social World\' is visible"
which means the text was NOT found.\n\nWait, looking at the view_match_list fail
ure hierarchy, the login page IS visible with all the elements. So `view_match_l
ist` actually successfully logged in (the login subflow completed), but then fai
led at `tab_messages`. The screenshot for view_match_list shows the login page i
s still visible AFTER login - meaning the login didn\'t actually navigate away. 
But wait, looking at the commands JSON for view_match_list, the tapOn "登录" was
COMPLETED, and then the next command was `tapOn: id: tab_messages` which FAILED.
The hierarchy at the time of failure shows the login page is still there!\n\nThi
s suggests that the login API call failed or the app stayed on the login page. B
ut `login` flow passed... Hmm. Actually the `login` flow doesn\'t assert anythin
g after tapping login - it just taps login and that\'s it. So `login` passes eve
n if login fails!\n\nLet me re-read the `login` flow:\n```yaml\n- launchApp:\n  
 clearState: true\n- runFlow: includes/login-as-test-user.yaml\n# 断言：登录成功
后应跳转（根据实际路由调整）\n# 如果登录成功进入首页，可取消下面注释：\n# - asse
rtVisible: "首页"\n```\n\nSo `login` flow PASSES because it only verifies the lo
gin form UI, not the actual login success. The `swipe_recommendations` and `view
_match_list` flows also use `login-as-test-user.yaml` and then try to interact w
ith post-login UI, but since there\'s no backend running, the login fails and th
ey stay on the login page.\n\nWait, but `setup` flow expects to see "完善资料" i
mmediately after `clearState: true` - that would only work if the user was alrea
dy logged in and the profile was incomplete. But `clearState: true` clears all s
tored tokens, so the user would be logged out.\n\nSo the failures are:\n1. **ope
n_drawer**: `assertVisible: "开发工具"` fails - the text might not be accessible
as regular text. Looking at the hierarchy, it shows `accessibilityText: "开发工
具"` and `resource-id: "dev_tools_toggle_button"`. Maestro\'s `assertVisible: "
开发工具"` looks for text, not accessibility text. I should change it to use the
